So as a content creator,
you're thinking--

00:13:52.140 --> 00:13:54.500
and they don't always
know this right away--

00:13:54.500 --> 00:13:56.430
should I mount it and
make it a point of view?

00:13:56.430 --> 00:14:00.956
Or is it just a fly on
the wall type of scenario?

00:14:00.956 --> 00:14:01.830
Sorry, I'm wandering.

00:14:01.830 --> 00:14:03.390
I'm supposed to stay
near this for the video.

00:14:03.390 --> 00:14:03.890
Sorry.

00:14:03.890 --> 00:14:07.564
So Brian, I told you you can
yell at me when I wander.

00:14:07.564 --> 00:14:08.980
BRIAN GRADY: I
don't like to yell.

00:14:08.980 --> 00:14:10.063
STEPHEN FROMKIN: I wander.

00:14:13.200 --> 00:14:17.770
So the question of camera
position is actually valid.

00:14:17.770 --> 00:14:23.360
What makes sense for the shot?

00:14:23.360 --> 00:14:25.190
And is it always the same?

00:14:25.190 --> 00:14:29.180
In one scene, is it
mounted to a person?

00:14:29.180 --> 00:14:30.870
And in another, is it not?

00:14:33.570 --> 00:14:39.760
The-- was it Neil who
was showing us the video,

00:14:39.760 --> 00:14:45.777
the CGI video, where the police
officer, we're tracking him.

00:14:45.777 --> 00:14:46.610
We're following him.

00:14:46.610 --> 00:14:50.390
And wham, now we are him.

00:14:50.390 --> 00:14:52.800
That's an interesting approach.

00:14:52.800 --> 00:14:56.760
But is that what the
content creator wants?

00:14:56.760 --> 00:14:57.850
I don't know.

00:14:57.850 --> 00:15:00.550
I'm telling you about a call
I literally had the other day

00:15:00.550 --> 00:15:01.630
so we don't know yet.

00:15:01.630 --> 00:15:04.330
We don't know where
this is going to end.

00:15:04.330 --> 00:15:07.210
The next question
is, well, where are

00:15:07.210 --> 00:15:10.170
you going to put this media?

00:15:10.170 --> 00:15:13.540
Is it going to go
to YouTube 360?

00:15:13.540 --> 00:15:15.060
Is it going to go to an app?

00:15:15.060 --> 00:15:21.760
Do you want it for Oculus or
Gear, Cardboard, everything?

00:15:21.760 --> 00:15:23.860
Because depending on what
you're going to shoot

00:15:23.860 --> 00:15:26.377
or where you're
going to distribute,

00:15:26.377 --> 00:15:28.460
you want to think about
that when you're shooting.

00:15:28.460 --> 00:15:30.990
It's like traditional,
a traditional 16 by 9.

00:15:30.990 --> 00:15:35.075
Well, what are my deliverables?

00:15:35.075 --> 00:15:37.450
So we're constantly talking
about what those deliverables

00:15:37.450 --> 00:15:41.250
might be and how we
can facilitate the best

00:15:41.250 --> 00:15:44.147
workflow for that delivery.

00:15:44.147 --> 00:15:45.980
The other thing that
comes into play-- and I

00:15:45.980 --> 00:15:48.713
jumped ahead on the whole
sort of delivery format thing.

00:15:48.713 --> 00:15:51.990
But back to camera position,
what about camera movement?

00:15:51.990 --> 00:15:58.260
If it's not mounted to a person,
and it's-- is it in a fixed

00:15:58.260 --> 00:16:01.200
point, or is it moving?

00:16:01.200 --> 00:16:05.290
Well, a still camera's sort of
maybe boring in a narrative.

00:16:05.290 --> 00:16:08.460
You want to sort of drift in
on a dolly shot or a slider.

00:16:08.460 --> 00:16:09.970
You're coming in on a jib arm.

00:16:09.970 --> 00:16:13.000
Well, you're going
to see all that.

00:16:13.000 --> 00:16:14.170
What about the lights?

00:16:14.170 --> 00:16:17.600
Narrative, your
lighting-- so all

00:16:17.600 --> 00:16:23.200
of these questions about
where do all the gear go?

00:16:23.200 --> 00:16:29.630
And where does-- we actually
had one scenario where somebody

00:16:29.630 --> 00:16:32.520
said, well, if we
shoot on a stage,

00:16:32.520 --> 00:16:36.365
do I have to get rid of craft
services and everything that--

00:16:36.365 --> 00:16:39.095
do I have to hide that stuff?

00:16:39.095 --> 00:16:40.600
No, you don't have to.

00:16:40.600 --> 00:16:44.370
You just-- you're
going to see it.

00:16:44.370 --> 00:16:46.492
Well, so can we just
take out the cameras?

00:16:46.492 --> 00:16:48.879
Yeah.

00:16:48.879 --> 00:16:50.170
Well then, what's behind there?

00:16:50.170 --> 00:16:52.940
Well, nothing.

00:16:52.940 --> 00:16:57.120
So they were-- but
none of it's wrong.

00:16:57.120 --> 00:16:58.060
None of this is wrong.

00:16:58.060 --> 00:16:58.920
Take out the camera.

00:16:58.920 --> 00:17:02.580
Shoot 180 and comp
something else in.

00:17:02.580 --> 00:17:08.420
The idea that you must go out
and shoot with all the cameras

00:17:08.420 --> 00:17:13.710
and come back with a perfect
sphere of live-action footage

00:17:13.710 --> 00:17:17.040
is kind of a tall order.

00:17:17.040 --> 00:17:18.540
And as I said at
the beginning, this

00:17:18.540 --> 00:17:20.930
is sort of a visual
effects workflow.

00:17:20.930 --> 00:17:24.020
You are capturing pixels.

00:17:24.020 --> 00:17:26.650
And after that, you're
manipulating them.

00:17:26.650 --> 00:17:30.130
Just by the very nature
of you're putting them

00:17:30.130 --> 00:17:31.700
in a stitching
program, and you're

00:17:31.700 --> 00:17:33.360
warping them and
distorting them,

00:17:33.360 --> 00:17:37.290
and you're materially
changing them,

00:17:37.290 --> 00:17:39.730
you might as well just
swallow the bitter pill

00:17:39.730 --> 00:17:44.260
that your in an effects
world now and trickery

00:17:44.260 --> 00:17:48.050
is part of the recipe.

00:17:48.050 --> 00:17:49.600
You have to deal with parallax.

00:17:49.600 --> 00:17:51.490
You have to deal with
the fact that there's

00:17:51.490 --> 00:17:54.107
going to be multiple
seams getting in the way

00:17:54.107 --> 00:17:55.690
and you're going to
have to hide that.

00:17:55.690 --> 00:17:59.330
And there's a monopod now you
have to paint out, or a tripod,

00:17:59.330 --> 00:18:00.544
or a drone that I can see.

00:18:00.544 --> 00:18:01.960
I wanted to see
the beautiful sky.

00:18:01.960 --> 00:18:03.550
Now there's a helicopter.

00:18:03.550 --> 00:18:10.810
So again, conversations that--
so speaking of narrative, let's

00:18:10.810 --> 00:18:13.295
talk about-- where is Neil?

00:18:13.295 --> 00:18:14.986
Neil, are you still here?

00:18:14.986 --> 00:18:22.924
See, he gave me such
great intro to really what

00:18:22.924 --> 00:18:25.090
I think is some of the most
interesting stuff, which

00:18:25.090 --> 00:18:28.290
is that indeed,
the language of VR

00:18:28.290 --> 00:18:30.990
is not the same as
the language of film.

00:18:30.990 --> 00:18:34.104
Screen direction-- everybody
knows what screen direction is?

00:18:34.104 --> 00:18:35.270
Somebody enters in the left.

00:18:35.270 --> 00:18:36.675
They exit on the right.

00:18:36.675 --> 00:18:38.145
If they exit on
the right now, it

00:18:38.145 --> 00:18:40.270
looks like they're going
back the other way, right?

00:18:40.270 --> 00:18:42.500
That's just one example
of screen direction.

00:18:42.500 --> 00:18:47.500
All of these things that we, as
content creators, as directors,

00:18:47.500 --> 00:18:51.382
as camera operators--
all of these things

00:18:51.382 --> 00:18:55.755
that we have taken as a
foundation for storytelling,

00:18:55.755 --> 00:18:59.770
for blocking, for mise en
scene, all of those things

00:18:59.770 --> 00:19:02.490
are completely turned
upside down, or inside out.

00:19:02.490 --> 00:19:06.230
Or they're all around
us, so to speak, right?

00:19:06.230 --> 00:19:09.660
So the questions don't end.

00:19:09.660 --> 00:19:12.990
And I'm not going to say
that I have all the answers.

00:19:12.990 --> 00:19:15.090
But the discussions are fun.

00:19:15.090 --> 00:19:19.820
So let's continue with
that for a second.

00:19:19.820 --> 00:19:26.350
Neil's example with "Heat"--
Pacino and De Niro at that

00:19:26.350 --> 00:19:30.160
awesome scene in the diner--
master shot coverage-- shot,

00:19:30.160 --> 00:19:32.280
reverse, shot, right?

00:19:32.280 --> 00:19:37.170
I've actually seen somebody
try to shoot coverage in VR.

00:19:37.170 --> 00:19:41.136
And so Jamie and Jolly,
and they're-- sorry,

00:19:41.136 --> 00:19:42.960
I'm walking away
from the light again.

00:19:42.960 --> 00:19:44.290
Sorry.

00:19:44.290 --> 00:19:48.420
So I shoot them,
and I want coverage.

00:19:48.420 --> 00:19:52.750
But even in the master shot,
if there's nothing back here,

00:19:52.750 --> 00:19:54.820
what's the point?

00:19:54.820 --> 00:19:57.050
Form meets function.

00:19:57.050 --> 00:20:00.590
So if I need that
type of shot, if I

00:20:00.590 --> 00:20:05.220
need that type of storytelling,
maybe I don't need 360.

00:20:05.220 --> 00:20:12.090
Maybe I can just tell
this in standard 16 by 9.

00:20:12.090 --> 00:20:13.750
But I want 360.

00:20:13.750 --> 00:20:14.510
OK, fine.

00:20:14.510 --> 00:20:16.960
So now let's build
the shot where

00:20:16.960 --> 00:20:19.820
it makes sense for
the camera position

00:20:19.820 --> 00:20:21.860
to be a part of
that conversation.

00:20:21.860 --> 00:20:27.160
Instead of it being a shot
on De Niro, a shot on Jamie,

00:20:27.160 --> 00:20:29.230
a shot on Pacino,
a shot on Jolly,

00:20:29.230 --> 00:20:31.520
instead of back and forth
and what we normally

00:20:31.520 --> 00:20:34.600
know as editorial
and composition,

00:20:34.600 --> 00:20:37.350
we're going to give the
camera a seat at the table.

00:20:37.350 --> 00:20:39.220
We're going to put
it at the table.

00:20:39.220 --> 00:20:42.810
And just as though
you were a part

00:20:42.810 --> 00:20:47.070
of the conversation in
"Heat," for example,

00:20:47.070 --> 00:20:50.550
you're going to sit there and
watch so that it's up to you

00:20:50.550 --> 00:20:56.180
when there's a dramatic
pause, who are you looking at.

00:20:56.180 --> 00:21:00.100
But as a filmmaker, as a content
creator, you have to decide,

00:21:00.100 --> 00:21:02.840
is that OK?

00:21:02.840 --> 00:21:06.818
Because what if somebody says,
I wonder what's over here now?

00:21:06.818 --> 00:21:08.630
[CLINKING]

00:21:08.630 --> 00:21:10.990
That's just part of the deal.

00:21:10.990 --> 00:21:15.070
So speaking of-- it's like
you did that on purpose.

00:21:15.070 --> 00:21:20.420
That was perfect-- sound, right?

00:21:20.420 --> 00:21:22.500
So I keep it quiet back there.

00:21:22.500 --> 00:21:24.220
Set, be quiet back there.

00:21:24.220 --> 00:21:25.610
But when I want
somebody to look,

00:21:25.610 --> 00:21:30.670
when I want somebody to jump,
I have that sound go off

00:21:30.670 --> 00:21:32.890
and I draw people's attention.

00:21:32.890 --> 00:21:34.050
I use peripheral.

00:21:34.050 --> 00:21:35.995
Because right now,
my composition-- I'm

00:21:35.995 --> 00:21:37.870
looking at this gentleman
right in the front.

00:21:37.870 --> 00:21:38.883
What's your name, sir?

00:21:38.883 --> 00:21:39.650
SEAN: Sean.

00:21:39.650 --> 00:21:40.300
STEPHEN FROMKIN: Hi, Sean.

00:21:40.300 --> 00:21:42.383
So Sean's sitting there
right at the front, right?

00:21:42.383 --> 00:21:45.890
So if I'm focusing on him, I
have sort of a-- let's call

00:21:45.890 --> 00:21:49.596
it a composition
I'm focusing on.

00:21:49.596 --> 00:21:51.970
Because I'm speaking to him,
so I'm focusing right there.

00:21:51.970 --> 00:21:55.780
But if somebody moves over
here, jumps up, starts mayhem,

00:21:55.780 --> 00:21:59.450
I have peripheral vision,
would use peripheral vision.

00:21:59.450 --> 00:22:01.390
You can do that.

00:22:01.390 --> 00:22:05.852
You have a viewable
area in VR, and then you

00:22:05.852 --> 00:22:07.810
have the area that you
need you go and look at.

00:22:07.810 --> 00:22:12.770
So what I'd like
to do is to stay

00:22:12.770 --> 00:22:16.470
on this sort of narrative
idea for a minute

00:22:16.470 --> 00:22:19.780
and open the floor up if
there's any specific questions.

00:22:19.780 --> 00:22:22.090
If anybody has a
question, whether it's

00:22:22.090 --> 00:22:24.950
related to what I'm
saying, what Neil said,

00:22:24.950 --> 00:22:29.160
what Todd said about
narrative filmmaking

00:22:29.160 --> 00:22:31.056
in VR, or narrative
content creation,

00:22:31.056 --> 00:22:34.826
because-- who here is a
director, or a producer,

00:22:34.826 --> 00:22:38.060
or controls the
camera, an editor?

00:22:38.060 --> 00:22:38.560
Thank you.

00:22:38.560 --> 00:22:39.110
OK,

00:22:39.110 --> 00:22:43.950
So if you're going
to get into 360,

00:22:43.950 --> 00:22:51.290
you are willfully giving up
the two most precious tools--

00:22:51.290 --> 00:22:55.160
composition and editorial.

00:22:55.160 --> 00:22:57.170
They're evolving.

00:22:57.170 --> 00:23:02.880
And how do you embrace that as
opposed to let it restrict you?

00:23:02.880 --> 00:23:06.180
What Todd was showing
us with the-- that's

00:23:06.180 --> 00:23:07.350
what they're testing.

00:23:07.350 --> 00:23:12.020
They're testing how to
embrace the fact that there's

00:23:12.020 --> 00:23:13.470
multiple things I can look at.

00:23:13.470 --> 00:23:17.680
They're using a certain
amount of points of interest

00:23:17.680 --> 00:23:22.110
to discern the
likelihood, and then

00:23:22.110 --> 00:23:26.985
provide cuts from shot to shot.

00:23:26.985 --> 00:23:29.030
That's exactly what
we're talking about,

00:23:29.030 --> 00:23:35.190
is changing the way we think
about editorial or composition.

00:23:35.190 --> 00:23:39.054
So any questions
to specific-- yeah?

00:23:39.054 --> 00:23:41.813
AUDIENCE: So based on
the experiments of VR

00:23:41.813 --> 00:23:44.411
that have been done
so far, are there

00:23:44.411 --> 00:23:47.333
types of stories that are
particularly well suited

00:23:47.333 --> 00:23:48.997
[INAUDIBLE]?

00:23:48.997 --> 00:23:50.830
STEPHEN FROMKIN: Types
of fictional stories?

00:23:50.830 --> 00:23:51.752
AUDIENCE: Either way.

00:23:51.752 --> 00:23:55.154
What seems to be working the
best [INAUDIBLE] storytelling?

00:23:55.154 --> 00:23:57.820
STEPHEN FROMKIN: What is working
the best are fictional stories.

00:23:57.820 --> 00:23:58.980
Let's start there.

00:23:58.980 --> 00:24:02.260
What's most challenging
is narrative,

00:24:02.260 --> 00:24:07.180
which is why it's so
fun to talk about,

00:24:07.180 --> 00:24:11.480
because we have a
certain language, right?

00:24:11.480 --> 00:24:14.860
I know I'm repeating
myself, but because of that,

00:24:14.860 --> 00:24:17.880
that's what's most
difficult. We're

00:24:17.880 --> 00:24:21.730
used to being
taken on a journey.

00:24:21.730 --> 00:24:29.710
And it somewhat
changes when we become

00:24:29.710 --> 00:24:32.180
in control of that
journey, whereas we

00:24:32.180 --> 00:24:33.690
were just sort of
passive as opposed

00:24:33.690 --> 00:24:37.440
to active in that process.

00:24:37.440 --> 00:24:40.240
What is working is things
that are experiential,

00:24:40.240 --> 00:24:43.800
somewhere where you can give
me the best seat in the house.

00:24:43.800 --> 00:24:45.420
If you can give me a seat at--

00:24:50.887 --> 00:24:52.174
AUDIENCE: The Super Bowl?

00:24:52.174 --> 00:24:53.340
STEPHEN FROMKIN: Super Bowl.

00:24:53.340 --> 00:24:55.570
See, I used Super Bowl
as an example earlier

00:24:55.570 --> 00:24:57.070
today so I didn't
want to double up,

00:24:57.070 --> 00:24:58.630
but it is my favorite example.

00:24:58.630 --> 00:25:00.950
50-yard line seats at
the Super, I'm probably

00:25:00.950 --> 00:25:02.270
not going to get those.

00:25:02.270 --> 00:25:06.910
But I might get a chance
to watch that in VR.

00:25:06.910 --> 00:25:08.830
An equally good example, soccer.

00:25:08.830 --> 00:25:10.540
Soccer fans?

00:25:10.540 --> 00:25:11.920
Rabid soccer fans, anybody?

00:25:11.920 --> 00:25:13.900
There's no rabid
soccer fans here?

00:25:13.900 --> 00:25:14.596
Brian?

00:25:14.596 --> 00:25:16.340
BRIAN GRADY: [INAUDIBLE].

00:25:16.340 --> 00:25:18.792
STEPHEN FROMKIN: OK.

00:25:18.792 --> 00:25:20.250
Pick a place where
you know there's

00:25:20.250 --> 00:25:22.736
going to be a lot of
energy-- a concert.

00:25:25.340 --> 00:25:29.687
A soccer match has a lot of
energy, especially when it's

00:25:29.687 --> 00:25:30.520
not in this country.

00:25:30.520 --> 00:25:32.754
When it's elsewhere,
it's more fun.

00:25:32.754 --> 00:25:33.730
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:25:33.730 --> 00:25:35.200
STEPHEN FROMKIN: Right.

00:25:35.200 --> 00:25:39.430
Those types of
places are where you

00:25:39.430 --> 00:25:43.240
can experience not just content,
but the energy because it

00:25:43.240 --> 00:25:45.986
becomes immersive.

00:25:45.986 --> 00:25:47.855
It becomes infectious.

00:25:47.855 --> 00:25:51.010
And it's sort of
what we deal with.

00:25:51.010 --> 00:25:53.710
As a viewer, we
see reaction shots.

00:25:53.710 --> 00:25:54.350
We see comedy.

00:25:54.350 --> 00:25:55.760
We see tears.

00:25:55.760 --> 00:26:00.090
We react to those
emotions generally.

00:26:00.090 --> 00:26:07.590
So if we feel
connected, it becomes

00:26:07.590 --> 00:26:12.070
infectious in the same
way that 16 by 9 would.

00:26:12.070 --> 00:26:16.110
That's why Chris Milk keeps
calling VR the great empathy

00:26:16.110 --> 00:26:16.610
machine.

00:26:20.180 --> 00:26:23.360
To continue answering your
question, what else is working

00:26:23.360 --> 00:26:30.110
are music videos because
there's not a lot of rules.

00:26:30.110 --> 00:26:33.070
You kind of do
whatever you want.

00:26:33.070 --> 00:26:34.409
Yes, sir?

00:26:34.409 --> 00:26:36.075
AUDIENCE: It's been
a great talk so far.

00:26:36.075 --> 00:26:37.821
My question is
actually about you

00:26:37.821 --> 00:26:41.065
said earlier regarding
[INAUDIBLE] shots

00:26:41.065 --> 00:26:43.560
don't work because
you lose background.

00:26:43.560 --> 00:26:45.306
If I understood that
correctly, you're

00:26:45.306 --> 00:26:47.053
talking about the "Heat" scene.

00:26:47.053 --> 00:26:48.716
And I'm nos so
familiar with that

00:26:48.716 --> 00:26:50.047
as I am with "Pulp Fiction."

00:26:50.047 --> 00:26:55.037
But imagine you've got Honey
Bunny and Ringo in the diner.

00:26:55.037 --> 00:26:58.031
And then you've got
Vincent Vega and Jules

00:26:58.031 --> 00:27:00.027
at the scene at the table.

00:27:00.027 --> 00:27:03.040
Why couldn't you shoot
from different views?

00:27:03.040 --> 00:27:06.340
STEPHEN FROMKIN: Well,
now you're talking.

00:27:06.340 --> 00:27:07.750
So that's a great example.

00:27:07.750 --> 00:27:08.250
Thank you.

00:27:08.250 --> 00:27:09.330
Did everybody hear that?

00:27:09.330 --> 00:27:10.180
AUDIENCE: No.

00:27:10.180 --> 00:27:16.270
STEPHEN FROMKIN: So the talky
scene with De Niro and Pacino,

00:27:16.270 --> 00:27:19.100
that's just two
guys at a table--

00:27:19.100 --> 00:27:22.610
OK, not physically
the most exciting.

00:27:22.610 --> 00:27:25.470
Performance-wise,
drama-wise, great.

00:27:25.470 --> 00:27:27.660
So you probably want
to be in there tight.

00:27:27.660 --> 00:27:29.270
